items.title: Request parser parser
items.body: A proposal so we can see the side by side w/ a devoted object. I think the initialization scheme is good in theory and for smaller parsing, it makes more sense, but I feel that having all of the code in one concise object is a better and more maintainable alternative than passing a stream to every object individually at the correct time. As it's written here in the parser, we can provide better access control to prevent users from calling in inappropriate order, we can see all of the parsing code in line and logically reason about what's being taken from the stream, and we prevent the stream from being controlled by several disparate objects. This was also slightly faster in my tests, here's some of the benches from last night. Although we should check on other people's systems as well. I think the advantages have less to do with absolute performance than with code organization and orthogonal systems.
